{
    "name": "Giant Porcupine",
    "type": "monster",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Ecology",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "<b>Environment</b> temperate forests or plains<br/><b>Organization</b> solitary, pair, or prickle (3\u20136)<br/><b>Treasure</b> none"
        },
        {
            "name": "Special Abilities",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "<b>Quills (Ex)</b> Any creature attacking a giant porcupine with light or one-handed melee weapons, natural weapons, or an unarmed strike takes 1d3 points of piercing damage. A creature that grapples a giant porcupine takes 2d4 points of piercing damage each round it does so."
        },
        {
            "name": "Description",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "More so than its smaller kin, the human-sized giant porcupine is a foul-tempered creature that is just as content chewing on carrion as on living creatures. Worse, giant porcupines are notorious in their almost foolhardy bravery, and have been known to attack creatures much larger than their own size. This unexpected aggression, when combined with their tangle of spearlike quills, makes the giant porcupine a dangerous foe."
        }
    ],
    "html": "<i>This gray, human-sized porcupine\u2019s round body is covered in sharp, striped quills.</i>",
